## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code is **timeout enforcement** with a **ResetAbort continuation** catch. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is removed entirely (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(() => work(), token)` | Task-based model; thread pool managed |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` | Cancellation-aware wait (.NET 6+) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Cooperative cancellation replaces preemptive abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` + `ResetAbort()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |

### Critical Pitfall: Work Won't Stop By Itself

**This is the biggest behavioral difference.** The original `Thread.Abort()` forcibly injected an exception into the running thread. Cooperative cancellation does **not** — the `Func<T> work` keeps running in the background after timeout unless it checks the token.

If `work` must actually stop, you need to thread the token through:

```csharp
// Caller must pass a cancellation-aware delegate
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Usage — work must cooperate:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Forgetting `using` on CTS** | `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`; leaking it leaks timers |
| **Blocking I/O ignores tokens** | `Thread.Sleep`, synchronous socket reads won't respond — use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures only *your* timeout is caught, not unrelated cancellations |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If `work` calls code you can't modify, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only true "abort" left |

### Async-First Alternative

If the caller can go async, prefer this — it avoids blocking a thread entirely:

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

**Bottom line:** The paradigm shifts from "kill the thread" to "ask the work to stop." Every long-running delegate must check the `CancellationToken` at regular intervals for timeouts to actually halt execution.
